{% block content %}

<p>I run a website called <a href="https://www.gittip.com/">Gittip</a>, which
is a weekly gift exchange. The idea is that you set up a small gift&mdash;up to
$100&mdash;to an open source programmer, a musician, an artist, etc., and every
Thursday we collect and distribute the money. We launched five months ago, and
we have about 550 active users exchanging $1,500 per week.</p>


<h3>The Broken Road</h3>

<p>Processing payments is complicated and fraught with regulations, so Gittip
depends on a third party to actually charge credit cards and deposit funds into
bank accounts. I launched using a service called <a
    href="https://samurai.feefighters.com/">Samurai</a> from a company called
<a href="http://feefighters.com/">FeeFighters</a>. In week two of Gittip,
FeeFighters dropped the ball, and when I went looking for support I found out
they&rsquo;d been <a
    href="http://blog.gittip.com/post/25565694263/how-not-to-get-acquired">acquired</a>
    by GroupOn and had turned off all their support channels. Bad news!
    :-(</p>

<p>I regrouped and switched to <a href="https://stripe.com/">Stripe</a>,
another credit card processing vendor. Stripe is gorgeous, really world class.
If you can work with them, you should. Unfortunately, I couldn&rsquo;t, because
Gittip is a <a
        href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/issues/67">
        marketplace</a>, and Stripe isn&rsquo;t designed for marketplaces. If
    you&rsquo;re an online store or non-profit you can use Stripe to collect
    credit card payments intended for you, but you&rsquo;re not supposed to use
    Stripe to accept payments on behalf of someone else.
    And that&rsquo;s what Gittip is all about. Stripe were very professional
    and gave me plenty of lead time, but they <a
        href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/issues/67#issuecomment-6553374">asked
        me to leave</a>. :-(</p>

<p>[<b>Update:</b> Stripe has since rolled out limited <a
    href="https://stripe.com/docs/connect">support</a> for marketplaces, though
Gittip still falls <a
    href="http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=4879710">outside</a> the use
cases.]</p>

<p>[<b>Update 2:</b> Stripe has now rolled out true <a
  href="https://stripe.com/blog/send-payouts-with-stripe">payouts</a> for
marketplaces.]</p>

<p>At this point Gittip was only a few weeks old and I was already looking for
my third payment processing vendor. I was in a conversation with <a
    href="https://www.braintreepayments.com/">Braintree</a>, another credit
card processor like Samurai and Stripe. They&rsquo;re a going concern and they
do work with marketplaces, notably Airbnb. However, being a marketplace, I was
looking at either fudging my application or jumping through significant extra
hoops to get going on their system. :-(</p>

<p>And that&rsquo;s when Balanced showed up.</p>


<h3>Engineering as Marketing</h3>

<p>I first heard of Balanced when they were called PoundPay. Someone in the
Gittip community put them on my radar and I started a <a
    href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/issues/78">ticket</a>.  I
was wary because they didn&rsquo;t seem to have much market traction, and I had
already been burned by one startup, FeeFighters. But Balanced were hungry, and
proactively pursued the relationship. CEO Matin Tamizi <a
    href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/issues/22#issuecomment-6792282">showed
    up</a> on GitHub.
Jareau Wade, co-founder in charge of sales and marketing, made <a
    href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/issues/22#issuecomment-7022618">his
    case</a> in public. They showed up on <a
    href="https://twitter.com/whit537/status/221274720388132864">IRC</a> and <a
    href="https://twitter.com/jkwade/status/223218256704581632">Twitter</a>.
We hammered out the details of our relationship on an <a
    href="http://sync.in/ep/pad/view/gittip-balanced/cYv4B118eQ">etherpad</a>,
with lots of community involvement via IRC. Then Balanced blew me away: one of
their engineers, Marshall Jones, made a <a
    href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/pull/137">pull request</a>
integrating Gittip with their service. :-)</p>

