<p>Balanced didn&rsquo;t stop there. Designer Damon Chin contributed a <a
    href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/issues/66#issuecomment-7268449">comp</a>
for a new visual design. When Gittip started to get hit by fraudsters&mdash;I
ended up calling it the <a
    href="http://blog.gittip.com/post/35314128322/the-delpan-incident">Delpan
    Incident</a>&mdash;risk officer Ganesh Venkataraman <a
    href="https://github.com/gvenkataraman/www.gittip.com">forked</a> the
Gittip repo to start work on fraud signaling, and ended up contributing a fraud
analysis based on data already in Balanced. We&rsquo;ve even had Tim
Nguyen&mdash;<i>their lawyer</i>&mdash;show up <i>on GitHub</i> and participate
in a <a
    href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/issues/96#issuecomment-6979153">discussion</a>
of the tax implications of Gittip. Let me say that again: the in-house general
counsel for one of my business partners joined a public discussion of tax law
on a social network for programmers. In the words of another lawyer friend of
mine, &ldquo;Gold fucking star!&rdquo;</p>


<h3>Challenges</h3>

<p>Suffice it to say, Gittip and Balanced are close partners at this point.
It&rsquo;s a good thing, too, because we&rsquo;re facing significant challenges
together.</p>

<p>When Gittip&rsquo;s first brush with fraud went down, former Balanced
employee Shawnee Cook came out of the woodwork with some <a
    href="http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=4744982">ugly accusations</a>
about Matin and Balanced. Factoring out the frustration, her story might still
cast <a href="http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=4795495">a shadow of a
    doubt</a> on Balanced&rsquo;s ability to contain fraud. Matin has addressed
this <a href="http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=4744929">briefly</a>. To my
mind, Balanced&rsquo;s main value proposition is being able to programmatically
verify identity and approve merchants. You feed a name, address, and date of
birth to their API, and they give you an instant
&ldquo;yea&rdquo; or &ldquo;nay.&rdquo; No days or hours of waiting, no
redirects off my website. That&rsquo;s new and exciting. It&rsquo;s also really
hard. Balanced is blazing a trail. I can understand some stolen credit cards
leaking through, but, personally, I was kind of surprised to find people
spoofing identity on the bank account side with such apparent ease. No one
expects perfect, 100% fraud-free performance, and so far I&rsquo;m trusting
that Balanced is managing fraud well enough that this model is going to work.
We&rsquo;re in this together.</p>

<p>While I&rsquo;m saying uncomfortable things, I&rsquo;ll also say that, in
terms of fit and finish, the Balanced API and dashboard is not as gorgeous as
Stripe. But, then again, what is? Gittip is flimsy in comparison to both. More
importantly, Balanced isn&rsquo;t really a direct competitor to Stripe. Stripe
is perfecting a well-understood problem, credit card payments.  Balanced is
innovating.  Balanced handles credit card payments, and then adds something new
and different: a merchant approval API. For Stripe, credit card payments are
the product. For Balanced, they&rsquo;re a feature. That said, Balanced&rsquo;s
API and UI execution is well above average, and they do respond promptly to
feedback.</p>


<h3>Open Partnership</h3>

<p>Gittip and Balanced are in an <a
    href="http://blog.gittip.com/post/28351995405/open-partnerships">open
    partnership</a>. This means we&rsquo;re not acting behind closed doors.
I&rsquo;ve had two cell phone calls with Matin, one when we were first getting
to know one another, and a second after a downtime <a
    href="https://github.com/balanced/balanced-api/issues/41">
    incident</a>. I talked privately with Tim and Ganesh during Delpan. And
I&rsquo;ve had a few private IRC chats with Jareau. Only once has Jareau asked
me for a marketing referral that I wasn&rsquo;t comfortable giving; I told him
as much and we got on with life. He approached me about writing this blog post,
something I&rsquo;d been thinking about doing anyway. I
hope to visit with them next time I&rsquo;m in Palo Alto. We are collaborating
closely, and we&rsquo;re doing it out in the open, mostly on GitHub, Twitter,
Hacker News, and IRC.</p>

<p>Open partnership also means that others are welcome at the table.
There&rsquo;s a lively <a
    href="https://www.balancedpayments.com/community">community</a> growing up
around Balanced. They have other <a
    href="https://www.balancedpayments.com/#community">clients</a>, of
course. But look also at Balanced&rsquo;s welcoming attitude when I&rsquo;ve
invited other companies to join them at my table: <a
    href="https://twitter.com/balanced/status/230007562752364544">Dwolla</a>,
<a
    href="https://github.com/whit537/www.gittip.com/issues/210#issuecomment-7474026">SpreedlyCore</a>,
<a href="https://twitter.com/balanced/status/273828088482258944">WePay</a>.
They&rsquo;re committed to openness to the point of discussing partnership with
seemingly direct competitors. Gold star.</p>

<p>Balance is not just practicing openness with Gittip, either. They&rsquo;re
really taking
    it <a
        href="https://www.balancedpayments.com/docs/overview#about-balanced">on
        board</a> as a company value&mdash;all the more remarkable because
    they&rsquo;re in payments, which is pretty much the last place I expect to
    find openness. As Jareau <a
        href="https://twitter.com/jkwade/status/236508468729765888">says</a>,
    &ldquo;imagine if our nation&rsquo;s biggest banks&rdquo; were run openly.
    What does this look like? Balanced isn&rsquo;t just reacting to market
    feedback on Twitter and StackOverflow. They&rsquo;re not just open-sourcing
    parts of their <a
        href="https://github.com/balanced/status.balancedpayments.com">infrastructure</a>.
    Balanced is <a href="https://github.com/balanced/balanced-api">designing
        their product</a> in public. They&rsquo;re holding <i>internal design
        discussions</i> in public on GitHub. Even if no one external comments
    on this or that ticket, the whole thing is there for clients, potential
    clients&mdash;even competitors!&mdash;to see. That&rsquo;s transparency.
    They even discuss <a
        href="https://github.com/balanced/balanced-api/issues/48"><i>pricing</i></a>
    in public. Wow!</p>

<p>Openness is guaranteed to feel destabilizing and threatening at times, and
unless it&rsquo;s a core value, it can be hard to stick with it. Balanced
&ldquo;gets&rdquo; openness.</p>


<h3>Why I Love Balanced</h3>

<p>Why do I <i>like</i> Balanced? I like Balanced because they offer a solid
merchant approval API that, as far as I&rsquo;m aware, isn&rsquo;t available
anywhere else. Why do I <i>love</i> Balanced? I love Balanced because they
believe in transparency and openness, and they stop at nothing to help me
succeed.</p>

<p>Want to build a marketplace? We&rsquo;d love to have you in the <a
    href="https://www.balancedpayments.com/">Balanced community</a>.</p>

